            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this cross stitch calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool helps you go from a chart’s stitch count to the exact
                fabric size you need, including borders and extra fabric for
                framing or finishing. It also supports stitching over 2 threads
                on linen/evenweave and suggests common frame openings.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Formula for stitched design size</h3>
              <p>
                The key idea is the <strong>effective fabric count</strong> in
                stitches per inch:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Effective count</strong> (stitches/inch) =</p>
                <p style="margin-left: 1rem">fabric count ÷ stitching factor</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Over 1 thread → stitching factor = 1</li>
                  <li>Over 2 threads → stitching factor = 2</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  <strong>Stitched width (inches)</strong> = stitches<span
                    style="font-size: 0.9em"
                    >&nbsp;wide</span
                  >
                  ÷ effective count
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Stitched height (inches)</strong> = stitches<span
                    style="font-size: 0.9em"
                    >&nbsp;high</span
                  >
                  ÷ effective count
                </p>
                <p>To convert to centimeters, multiply inches by 2.54.</p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Adding borders and framing margins</h3>
              <p>
                You usually want blank fabric around the stitched area. This
                calculator separates that into:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Design border</strong> – the visible blank area around
                  your stitches.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Extra framing margin</strong> – extra fabric for
                  lacing, stretching, or generous matting.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>Total fabric size is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Total width</strong> = stitched width + 2 × (border +
                  framing margin)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Total height</strong> = stitched height + 2 × (border
                  + framing margin)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Choosing fabric count and stitching style</h3>
              <p>
                The same chart will finish at different sizes on different
                fabrics. For example, a 140 × 100 stitch design:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  On 14-count Aida (over 1): 140 ÷ 14 = 10″ wide, 100 ÷ 14 ≈
                  7.1″ high.
                </li>
                <li>
                  On 28-count linen (over 2): effective count = 28 ÷ 2 = 14, so
                  the size is identical to 14-count Aida.
                </li>
                <li>
                  On 18-count Aida (over 1): 140 ÷ 18 ≈ 7.8″ wide, 100 ÷ 18 ≈
                  5.6″ high.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use the fabric count and stitching style controls to experiment
                and see how your finished size changes.
              </p>

              <h3>4. How much extra fabric should you allow?</h3>
              <p>Common recommendations:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Minimum:</strong> 2″ (5&nbsp;cm) extra fabric on each
                  side beyond the stitched area.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Comfortable for framing:</strong> 3–4″
                  (7.5–10&nbsp;cm) per side, especially for larger pieces.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pillows/ornaments:</strong> often 1–2″ (2.5–5&nbsp;cm)
                  per side is enough.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In this calculator, you can set both the visible border and the
                extra framing margin separately, so you can match your
                finisher’s or framer’s preferences.
              </p>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose your chart is 160 × 120 stitches and you want to stitch
                on 32-count linen over 2 threads.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Effective count = 32 ÷ 2 = 16 stitches per inch.</li>
                <li>
                  Stitched width = 160 ÷ 16 = 10″; stitched height = 120 ÷ 16 =
                  7.5″.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You choose a 1″ border and 2″ extra framing margin per side.
                </li>
                <li>Total extra per side = 1″ + 2″ = 3″.</li>
                <li>
                  Total width = 10″ + 2 × 3″ = 16″; total height = 7.5″ + 2 × 3″
                  = 13.5″.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                You’d cut a piece of fabric at least 16″ × 13.5″ (about 40.6 ×
                34.3&nbsp;cm).
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Can I use this for evenweave and linen?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Choose the fabric count (e.g. 28, 32, 36) and set
                <strong>stitching style</strong> to “Over 2 threads”. The
                calculator automatically halves the effective count so your
                stitched size is correct.
              </p>

              <h3>What if my chart already lists the finished size?</h3>
              <p>
                You can reverse the process: enter the stitch count and fabric
                count shown on the chart to confirm the finished size, then
                adjust the fabric count to see how big it would be on a
                different fabric.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this account for fractional stitches or backstitch?</h3>
              <p>
                Fractional stitches and backstitch don’t change the overall
                stitch count grid, so they don’t affect the fabric size. As long
                as your stitch count is correct, the calculator’s results will
                be accurate.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I choose a frame size from the results?</h3>
              <p>
                Use the <strong>stitched design size</strong> as the minimum
                opening. If you want a mat border, add that to each side. Then
                pick the nearest standard frame size that is equal to or
                slightly larger than that opening. The “Suggested frame
